WebStorm and VS Code handle `@example` tags differently. I had to use some workarounds to get decent, consistent rendering on both editors. JSDoc uses `` tags to add captions to examples. Both VS Code and WebStorm do not support it. I've employed the following workaround. 
 * @example Space ZeroWidthSpace Space ```` HTMLEncodedCaption
The backticks cause WebStorm to hide the line, so _`ZeroWidthSpace`_ is used to ensure WebStorm renders the caption. WebStorm renders the caption immediately following `Example:` without whitespace. The _`ZeroWidthSpace`_ along with the following _`Space`_ adds padding to improve readability. So why are the backticks necessary? VS Code starts off parsing `@example` tags assuming that it's JavaScript. The first 3 backticks kicks it in to Markdown mode. The fourth backtick hides a backtick in VS Code and the first 3 backticks in WebStorm. This causes a empty (but padded) inline code block to render in VS Code. The caption then follows. It must be HTML encoded as WebStorm will interpret any HTML tags as HTML instead of text. In addition to all of this, WebStorm requires the caption to be entirely on one line. The example body is enclosed in an HTML code block. VS Code will render this as syntax highlighted code. WebStorm renders this as plain text. The HTML block must be left-aligned and lines cannot start with `*` as VS Code includes the spaces and asterisk when rendering. Empty lines are collapsed in WebStorm. In order to preserve them, a _`ZeroWidthSpace`_ is added to the line (using _`Space`_ causes the `@example` block to terminate early). The following TSLint rules had to be disabled: * `jsdoc-format` Code blocks cannot include JSDoc line leader. * `max-line-length` Caption must be single line. * `no-irregular-whitespace` Usages of zero-width space.

This PR adds a GenericEvent type and make it default in generic type functions like responder.on.
This Generic type allow the use of custom event properties without having to define an interface and so simplify the transition from js to ts in a project using [cote](https://github.com/dashersw/cote) without changing the behavior for people using typings on those generically typed functions.

As raised by @makepost in PR [29159](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/29159) a simple 
`interface Event {
  type: string;
  [key: string]: any;
}`

will not suits our needs as it would stop raising error on typed usage of those functions. But I think keeping the old behavior that raise error even on an untyped usage on those function is not the good way as it make the migration between ts and js harder by forcing developpers to update all cote projects with custom interfaces. 
Maybe this solution could be a good compromise.

---

#### Summary of changes

##### [`isNumeric`](https://api.jquery.com/jQuery.isNumeric/) can not be a user defined type guard. (577ca4af0f54c0cea1fd3f2b21f29230609d2d50)

`isNumeric` can return true for strings in addition to numbers, but only for a subset of either. It'll return `false` for `NaN` (which TypeScript treats as a number) and for strings which cannot be parsed as a number.

##### [`isPlainObject`](https://api.jquery.com/jquery.isplainobject/) can not be a user defined type guard. (6258aa2cb2868b8606d82aabd34acf940fc03470)

Due to the imprecise way with how [`PlainObject`](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/5dc1165fb11875022d76f32554ca96c01804d8a1/types/jquery/index.d.ts#L5899) is declared, `isPlainObject` can not be a user defined type guard.

##### Improve declarations of [`jQuery.data()`](https://api.jquery.com/jquery.data/)/[`.data()`](https://api.jquery.com/data/) to catch unintentionally passing `undefined` as a value. (a05dc4290b75d52b6c68c3ca19038f615cada2b6)

Passing `undefined` to `.data()` calls the getter overload instead of the setter. The declarations correctly handled the case where value is _only_ of type `undefined`. However, the more likely scenario is that a value that is _possibly_ undefined is passed instead. Previously, this would resolve exclusively to the setter overload (which is incorrect if the value is actually undefined). It is now an error to call `.data()` with a value that is possibly undefined.

##### Improve declaration of [`css()`](https://api.jquery.com/jQuery.cssHooks/#defining-complete-csshook). (acf60379580e8bf0beec82844ba5b5ba6e931a19)

The 2nd parameter is now of type `string` (previously `any`).
